A: You need to flush the PrintWriter after writing the lines. Without flushing, the data may not be sent immediately.
Try this:
PrintWriter printWriter = ...
printWriter.write("1\n");
printWriter.write("2\n");
printWriter.write("3\n");
printWriter.flush();

Also, make sure you close the PrintWriter after you're done writing.
printWriter.close();


A: You need to add a newline character ("\n") after each line you want to send. This tells the BufferedReader that you're done with the current line and it can start reading the next one.
Try this:
PrintWriter printWriter = ...
printWriter.write("1\n");
printWriter.write("2\n");
printWriter.write("3\n");
printWriter.flush();

ServerSocket serverSocket = ...
Socket socket = serverSocket.accept();
BufferedReader bufferedReader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(socket.getInputStream()));
System.out.println(bufferedReader.readLine());

This should print "1" when you call bufferedReader.readLine().

